PAGE 55, line 1. ordinatis a. deo. In this preface the author is endeavouring to justify the double position of statesman and ecclesiastic which had marked three generations of his family. His political philosophy is that of a strong adherent of the king as against the conception of a separate secular and ecclesiastical state, and he makes use of almost the same language and the same citations as Hugh of Fleury in his treatise De regia poteslate (c. 1100). All power is from G0d; therefore in serving kings, the ecclesiastic serves God; kingly power is dependent on dignity, and on wealth; there may be bad kings, but the judgement of their wickedness is for God; their subjects must obey them, and look after their wealth without regarding the use to which it is put.
